-- Kansai Electric, Nissen, Rakuten, Ryosan, Uny: Japanese Stocks
-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a
-- 2012-02-21T02:56:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-21/kansai-electric-nissen-rakuten-ryosan-uny-japanese-stocks.html
Japan ’s  Nikkei 225 Stock Average (NKY) 
fell 4.30, or 0.1 percent, to 9,480.79 at the 11:30 a.m. trading
break in  Tokyo . The following are among the most active shares
in the Japanese  market  today. Stock symbols are in parentheses
after company names.  Shipping lines:  Nippon Yusen K.K. (9101)  (9101 JT), Mitsui O.S.K.
Lines Ltd. (9104 JT) and  Kawasaki Kisen Kaisha Ltd. (9107)  (9107 JT)
gained after the Nikkei newspaper reported the three shipping
companies may sell vessels to ease a glut of capacity.  Nippon Yusen  rose 1.2 percent to 245 yen. Mitsui O.S.K.
climbed 1.9 percent to 375 yen. Kawasaki Kisen added 1.6 percent
to 187 yen.  CDG Co. (2487 JQ), a provider of marketing services and
promotional goods, soared 8 percent to 2,220 yen, the highest
level since listing in June 2006. The company said it will
conduct a 3-for-1 stock split.  Daiichikosho Co. (7458 JQ), a maker of karaoke equipment,
climbed 4 percent to 1,596 yen. The company said it will spend
as much as 1.1 billion yen ($14 million) to buy back as much as
0.95 percent of its outstanding shares.  DeNA Co. (2432 JT), a social-networking service provider,
rallied 6.8 percent to 2,542 yen. DeNA and  South Korea ’s web-
portal operator Daum Communications Corp. (035720 KS) said they
have started providing “Daum Mobage,” a South Korean version
of DeNA’s social gaming platform, targeting 10 million users
within a year.  Kansai Electric Power Co. (9503 JT), a utility, lost 2.8
percent to 1,393 yen. The company halted the 70-megawatt No. 3
reactor at its Takahama nuclear plant in western Japan for
regular maintenance, Yusuke Inoue, a spokesman for the utility,
said by phone today.  Misawa & Co. (3169)  (3169 JT), a furniture retailer, surged by its
daily limit of 150 yen, or 17 percent, to 1,058 yen. Pretax
profit from operations probably more than doubled to almost 400
million yen in the year ended January as newly opened stores
boosted sales, the Nikkei newspaper reported. That number would
be about 20 million yen more than the retailer’s estimate, the
report said, without citing anyone.  Nissen Holdings Co. (8248 JO) jumped 8.3 percent to 391 yen.
The mail order business operator said it will raise about 4.57
billion yen from the sale of shares to  UCC Holdings (UCCUEZ)  (UCCUEZ JP),
a closely held coffee bean distributor.  Rakuten Inc. (4755)  (4755 JQ), an online shopping site operator,
advanced 3.5 percent to 77,100 yen. The company said it will
conduct a 100-for-1 stock split and adopt a minimum trading lot
of 100 shares.  Ryosan Co. (8140)  (8140 JT) slumped 4.4 percent to 1,694 yen. The
electronic components distributor cut its full-year net-income
forecast 16 percent to 2.1 billion yen, citing higher taxes. The
company also halved its planned second-half dividend to 20 yen
per share.  Starcat Cable Network Co. (4339 JQ) soared by its daily
limit of 7,000 yen, or 15 percent, to 54,900 yen, the biggest
gain since November 2004. Community Network Center will buy the
cable television operator in a tender offer for 79,300 yen per
share, according to a statement from Starcat.  Uny Co. (8270)  (8270 JT) increased 4.2 percent to 791 yen. Daiwa
Securities Group Inc. boosted the investment rating for the
department store operator to “outperform” from “neutral.”  Zuken Inc. (6947)  (6947 JT), a developer computer systems for
engineering and design, jumped 8.9 percent to 659 yen, en route
for the steepest advance since November 2008. The company said
it will pay a special dividend of 10 yen per share to mark its
35th anniversary, boosting its planned second-half dividend to
17 yen.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Norie Kuboyama in Tokyo at 
